<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-391-076  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 391 076.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC Professional  Dec 1990 v9 n13 p78(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>RMS buffers for indexed files. (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Walker, Betty Steele.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Multibuffering, done correctly, can decrease program I/O time.andO;Indexed file I/O performance can be increased by the correct useof RMS buffering.andP;  The factors involved in assigning buffersinclude the file size, number of keys in a file, and the type ofprocessing being done.andP;  In VMS there are three levels for localI/O buffers: system, process, and program.andP;  Program is checkedfirst, then process level, and then system level.andP;  The processbuffer count should be used to balance I/O needs at the individualuser level.andP;  Other factors that affect I/O activity includeheavily shared files that can benefit from global buffers,reorganizing files can increase I/O performance, and breakinglarge files into smaller files will help performance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Performance ImprovementI/O ManagementTutorialBuffering.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   RMS system and process buffer counts. (chart)Final design phase of EDIT/FDL. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>